{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ae68bd2b-c801-470b-b4d0-6018b9474181","content":"It works. `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` is available out of the box in .NET 11. Here's the full program:\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Text.Json;\n\nvar person = new Person(\"Alice\", 30);\n\nvar options = new JsonSerializerOptions\n{\n    PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase,\n    WriteIndented = true\n};\n\nstring json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(person, options);\nConsole.WriteLine(json);\n\npublic record Person(string name, int age);\n```\n\n**Output:**\n```json\n{\n  \"Name\": \"Alice\",\n  \"Age\": 30\n}\n```\n\nThe key detail: since your record uses lowercase parameter names (`name`, `age`), the generated properties are also lowercase. `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` (new in .NET 11) converts them to `Name` and `Age` in the JSON output — no custom naming policy needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6001c9e7-6e6e-470a-a71f-45b48ed69070","outputTokens":230,"requestId":"7C21:2B8350:4289F8:4CBD3A:6A051DB1"},"id":"ae83f28c-d96c-42bd-94cf-8632f1d363f5","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:57:38.863Z","parentId":"95592eea-f879-45fd-baea-ae9340c1ed82"}
